--> Arrays and Array

1. array (lowercase) → Built-in data structure

An array is a language-level feature in Java.
It is not a class.
It is a fundamental container that holds multiple values of the same type.

Example:
int[] numbers = {1, 2, 3};
char[] x = a.toCharArray();

Characteristics:

Fixed size
Stores elements directly
Index-based
Created using new or array literals
No built-in methods except .length field

Example operations:
numbers[0] // access element
numbers.length // array size

2. Arrays (capital A) → Utility Class
   Arrays is a class from java.util package.
   import java.util.Arrays;

This class provides static utility methods for working with arrays.

Common operations provided by Arrays:

Sorting → Arrays.sort(array)
Comparing → Arrays.equals(array1, array2)
Binary search → Arrays.binarySearch(array)
Filling → Arrays.fill(array, value)

Converting to string → Arrays.toString(array)

Example from your code:
Arrays.sort(x);
Arrays.sort(y);
Arrays.equals(x, y);

These are helper methods, not part of the array itself.

4. Simple Explanation

array → the actual storage box
Arrays → a toolbox containing tools to work on that box

